The democracy summit ended, and Biden said that the fire of freedom will never go out
The online "Summit for Democracy", convened by US President Biden and attended by governments, civil society and private sector leaders from 110 countries around the world, ended on Friday (December 10th).
Biden said in his closing speech that the fire of freedom burns in the hearts of everyone in the world, and autocratic regimes can never extinguish it.
He also said that he plans to hold the second global "democracy summit" next year.
Tang Feng, a representative of the Taiwan government and an administrative councilor, and Luo Guancong, a Hong Kong democracy and human rights activist who is currently in exile in Britain, also spoke at the summit the next day.
Biden said: "We know how difficult the work before us is.
But we also know that we can rise to the challenge because, as I said before, as this summit has shown, the democratic world is everywhere.
Authoritarian regimes can never extinguish the slight fire of freedom, which burns in the hearts of people all over the world and everywhere. "
Biden also said that defending democracy requires the joint efforts of the whole society.
"As leaders of government, we have a responsibility to listen to our citizens, to reinforce the guardrails of democracy, to push for reform, to achieve transparent and accountable governance, to be more resilient to the cushions and shocks of authoritarianism, and to those who want to pursue power nakedly before the public good," he said.
The themes of the second day of the "Democracy Summit" are defending human rights, consolidating democracy and confronting authoritarianism, and countering digital authoritarianism and affirming democratic values.
This day coincides with International Human Rights Day.
In his opening speech on the same day, UN Secretary-General Guterres also said that the cause of democracy is facing challenges all over the world, especially those brought by emerging digital technologies.
He said: "It is time to reaffirm common values and positions and democratic resilience.
This requires deepening social dialogue, addressing inequalities, fighting corruption, renewing the social contract, investing in quality education and expanding opportunities for women and girls.
It also requires a firm condemnation of all forms of populism, nativism and extremism, including using all the tools provided by the technological revolution. "
Luo Guancong, a Hong Kong democracy and human rights activist, addressed the summit via pre-recorded video, reminding participants to keep an eye on the human rights situation in Hong Kong and ethnic Chinese minorities such as Uighurs and Tibetans.
He said: "For a long time, the world has accepted the rise of China without establishing a mechanism to hold it accountable.
That is why politicians and civil society leaders must cooperate.
We must use everything (resources) we have to make sure that the revival of democracy is our top priority. "
Luo Guancong also called on the free world to unite against the threat of the Communist Party of China.
He said: "Maybe some of you are afraid to annoy General Secretary 　, maybe some of you don't want to lose the Chinese market, maybe some of you don't realize the threat [CPC] poses to our democratic values.
And that's why we failed.
That's why we have to change. "
Tang Feng, an administrative councilor of the Executive Yuan of Taiwan Province, attended the roundtable discussion on "Combating Digital Authoritarianism and Affirming Democratic Values" and released a "National Statement" by video, emphasizing that Taiwan Province stands at the forefront of confronting autocracy and authoritarianism.
He also shared his experience in fighting COVID-19 pandemic through information transparency and building mutual trust.
He said: "At a time when Taiwan's democracy is in the ascendant, we have always stood firmly at the forefront of the global fight against authoritarianism and played a leading role in promoting global freedom, democracy and human rights.
During the epidemic, authoritarian governments around the world rationalized human rights violations in the name of public health and collective interests, and global democracy showed signs of retrogression.
However, in Taiwan Province, we can control the epidemic without closing the city, and we can overcome false information without taking it off the shelves. "
At the same time as the second day of the "Democracy Summit", the U.S. Treasury Department announced that it would impose sanctions on 15 individuals and 10 entities in China, North Korea and other countries that were found to have seriously violated human rights, and at the same time impose investment restrictions on a Chinese company that was found to have used surveillance technology to assist in human rights violations.
