Vietnam People's Daily Network-Gulf Cooperation Council meets common challenges
Saudi Crown Prince Mohammed bin Salman's stops include Oman, the United Arab Emirates (UAE), Qatar, Bahrain and Kuwait.
Notably, this is Crown Prince Mohammed's first visit to Qatar since Saudi Arabia and its Arab allies imposed an embargo on Qatar in mid-2017, which led to the Gulf diplomatic crisis.
During the crisis, Saudi Arabia, the United Arab Emirates, Bahrain and Egypt severed diplomatic ties with Qatar and imposed a blanket embargo on it, accusing it of supporting terrorist groups while maintaining close ties with Iran.
Diplomatic tensions have seriously affected the internal unity of the GCC and had a negative impact on the economies of countries in the region.
Four Arab countries have blocked land, sea and air routes to Qatar.
This crisis was resolved only at the Gulf Cooperation Council summit in January 2021, and the Gulf countries signed an agreement mediated by the United States and Kuwait to move towards "unity and stability".
Saudi Arabia has reopened its border with Qatar.
Saudi Arabia and Egypt are spearheading efforts to restore relations with Qatar by appointing new ambassadors there.
The Gulf Arab countries resolve their differences in order to restore relations with Qatar, which stems from the requirement of unity for the interests of all countries and regional stability, and aims to meet common challenges.
During the Saudi Crown Prince's visit to Oman, the two sides agreed to open the first direct land passage between the two Gulf neighbors.
The 725-kilometer-long passage connecting the two countries will provide convenient conditions for citizens of the two countries to travel and integrate supply chains.
Saudi Arabia's Public Investment Fund (PIF) will invest US $5 billion in Oman, and enterprises of the two countries have signed 13 memorandums of understanding on cooperation worth US $30 billion.
The Saudi crown prince's visit to the Gulf states coincides with talks between Iran and world powers to salvage the Iran nuclear deal known as the "Joint Comprehensive Plan of Action" (JCPOA)-a deal condemned by Gulf Arab states for believing it could not resolve the missile issue with Iran.
Gulf countries have always regarded Iran as a long-term "competitor" and regarded Iran's nuclear program as a "threat" to regional security.
The Gulf states believe it is flawed not to resolve the Iranian missile issue and not to take action to curb Iranian activities in the region.
Under the background that the nuclear negotiations between major powers and Iran failed to meet the aspirations of Gulf countries, Saudi Arabia held direct negotiations with Iran.
Its goal is to contain the escalation of tensions in the region.
This is one of the factors slowing down the economic growth of GCC countries.
The upcoming GCC summit will be the first of its kind among GCC countries since the end of a dispute between some member states and Qatar.
This is an opportunity for the Gulf Cooperation Council to reassess the diplomatic achievements that have contributed to the restoration of the unity of the GCC, and at the same time propose measures to make its member States cooperate fully to meet common challenges and contribute to the stability and development of the Gulf countries.
