Xinhua News Agency, Washington, May 23 (Reporter Xu Jianmei) More than 130 Asian groups in the United States submitted complaints to the US Department of Education and the US Department of Justice on the 23rd, protesting against the discrimination of Asian applicants by three Ivy League schools-Yale University, Brown University and Dartmouth College in the enrollment process.
The Asian Education Alliance, which took the lead in initiating the complaint, held a press conference in Washington on the same day.
Zhao Yukong, chairman of the group, said at the press conference that in the past 10 years, the number of Asian applicants who meet the admission requirements of famous American schools has doubled, but the proportion of Asian applicants in these three famous American schools has basically remained at the same level.
Many studies have shown that these universities "discriminate against Asian applicants for a long time and systematically" in the so-called "comprehensive consideration" enrollment process.
Zhao Yukong said that the research of Sanders and other scholars in 2014 showed that among these three universities, Asians had the lowest admission rate among all ethnic groups relative to the number of applicants.
Data from the US Department of Education also show that among all Ivy League schools, Brown University and Dartmouth College have the lowest admission ratio for Asian students, while Yale University and Brown University have implemented de facto racial quotas for Asian applicants for more than 20 years.
Zhao Yukong told Xinhua that they expect that after submitting the complaint, the US Department of Education and the Department of Justice can launch an investigation and take measures to prevent these universities from continuing to discriminate against Asians in enrollment.
They also expect the complained universities to take the initiative to pay attention to this problem and change the enrollment policy for Asian Americans.
At present, the three universities complained have not yet responded.
The Asian Education Alliance was established in 2015. At that time, it complained about discrimination in Harvard University's enrollment, but the US Department of Education refused to accept it for procedural reasons.
In addition to Chinese American groups, the educational groups of Indian, Korean, Japanese and Pakistani Americans also participated in the complaint.
